04545nam a22005055i 9780773580787DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735807877 a10.1515/97807735807872doi  a(DE-B1597)657864  a(OCoLC)768490943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE101.N35 2010eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a971.01141 aNicholls, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFleeting Empire :bEarly Stuart Britain and the Merchant Adventurers to Canada /cAndrew Nicholls. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (277 p.) :b10 drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: On Filling the Gaps -- tThe Huron Mission and the Promise of New France -- tEarly English And British Expeditions In The North Atlantic Theatre -- tKing James VI/I and the Challenge of Anglo-Scottish Co-operation -- tThe Poet Courtier: Sir William Alexander and His Charter -- tThe Paper Colony: Charles’s Privateers and the Proxy War -- tThe Demands of Honour and Charles I’s Unfolding Strategy -- tA Man of Controversy: James Stewart of Killeith, Fourth Lord Ochiltree -- tMixed Motives and the Company of Merchant Adventurers to Canada -- tShifting Loyalties and the Case of the Embezzled Furs -- tLord Ochiltree’s Gamble and the Abandonment of Port Royal -- tThe Treaty of Saint–Gcrmain–En–Laye and the End of a Partnership -- tEpilogue: Not as Strangers -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore the future of North American rule was decided by the battle between British and French forces on the Plains of Abraham, Britain's emerging imperial interests were represented by ambitious merchants and privateers. A Fleeting Empire examines the lives and exploits of early European adventurers in North America, revealing the murky mix of self-interest, patriotism, and adventure that motivated them. The union of the English and Scottish crowns in 1603 gave rise to a new British seafaring community, which the early Stuart monarchy used to pursue some of the first commercial and colonial ventures in North America. Among those who sailed across the Atlantic were the Kirke brothers, who in 1629 forced Samuel de Champlain's surrender of Quebec, Sir William Alexander of Menstrie, a rising political figure and patentee of Nova Scotia, and James Stewart of Killeith, leader of a colony on Cape Breton Island. King Charles I was more concerned with brokering a peace with France than looking to the new world, so the gains of the merchant adventurers were short-lived, but their adventures provide a tantalizing glimpse of a moment of British colonial control, suggesting what might have been. Andrew Nicholls showcases the enterprises of knights and privateers alike, providing a fascinating account of early European colonies, commerce, and military force in North America. A Fleeting Empire forces us to see the early histories of Canada and the United States in a new light.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358078740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773580787423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773580787/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2